{{Infobox political party | name = Dagga Party | native_name = | lang1 = [[isiXhosa]] | name_lang1 = Iqela Lentsango | lang2 = | name_lang2 = | lang3 = | name_lang3 = | lang4 = | name_lang4 = | logo = Vote dagga.png | colorcode = DarkGreen | leader = Jeremy Acton | chairperson = | president = | deputy president = | secretary_general = | spokesperson = | founder = | leader1_title = | leader1_name = | leader2_title = | leader2_name = | leader3_title = | leader3_name = | slogan = | founded = {{Start date|2009|02|df=yes}} | dissolved = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | merger = | split = | predecessor = | merged = | successor = | headquarters = | newspaper = | student_wing = | youth_wing = | wing1_title = | wing1 = | wing2_title = | wing2 = | wing3_title = | wing3 = | membership_year = | membership = | ideology = [[Cannabis legalisation]] | position = | religion = | national = | international = | colours = | seats1_title = | seats1 = | seats2_title = | seats2 = | seats3_title = | seats3 = | seats4_title = | seats4 = | symbol = | flag = | website = {{url|daggaparty.org.za}} | country = South Africa | footnotes = }}
'''Iqela Lentsango: The Dagga Party of South Africa''' (more commonly known as the '''Dagga Party''') is a [[South Africa]]n political party founded in February 2009 by Jeremy Acton, who remains the party's leader. "Dagga" is a South African colloquial term for [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]], the legalisation of which forms the core of the party's platform.<ref name="8JointsADay">{{cite news|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2013-05-10-00-dagga-party-eight-joints-a-day-for-cape-politician|title=Dagga Party: Eight joints a day for Cape politician|date=10 May 2013|author=Glynnis Underhill|newspaper=[[Mail & Guardian]]|accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref> The Dagga Party was established to allow voters who support the legalisation of dagga to have representation in elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://citizen.co.za/149614/dagga-partys-election-hopes-smoke/|title=Dagga Party’s election hopes up in smoke|website=The Citizen|last1=Mitchley|first1=Alex|accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref>
The party failed to register with the [[Electoral Commission of South Africa|Independent Electoral Commission]] in order to contest the [[South African general election, 2014|2014 South African general election]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/0e6de50043685d48a322b7856359f483/Manyundefinedpoliticalundefinedpartiesundefinedwon%E2%80%99tundefinedmakeundefineditundefinedtoundefinedParliament:undefinedAnalyst-20142603|title=Many minor parties won’t make it to Parliament: Analyst|last=Sithole|first=Sthembiso|date=2014-03-26|work=SABC|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> missing the deadline because the required R200,000 registration fee could not be raised in time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ewn.co.za/2014/03/26/Dagga-party-misses-election-deposit-deadline|title=Dagga Party misses election deadline|website=Eyewitness News|last1=Davis|first1=Gaye|accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref>
The party's position is that cannabis users should have the same rights as people who use tobacco and alcohol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/local/2016/12/13/People-jailed-for-dagga-should-be-released-court-hears|title=People jailed for dagga should be released‚ court hears|last=Collins|first=Farren|website=Times LIVE|access-date=2016-12-18}}</ref>
Acton was one of the people responsible for bringing the case before a South African court which resulted in the [[Cannabis in South Africa#Partial decriminalisation|partial decriminalisation of dagga in South Africa]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.groundup.org.za/article/we-want-right-carry-cannabis-our-pockets-person-can-carry-cigarettes/|title=“We want the right to carry cannabis in our pockets like a person can carry cigarettes”|last=Hendricks|first=Ashraf|date=2017-05-06|work=Ground Up|access-date=2017-05-07|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref>
