{{Multiple issues| {{refimprove|date=August 2018}} {{orphan|date=December 2012}} {{notability|date=December 2012}} }}
'''Industrial antiterrorism''' is a term coined in 2012 by the union of [[military]] and engineering standards.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}
Industrial terrorism is [[terrorism]] whose sole purpose is to strike at the heart of the [[business]] and [[critical infrastructure]] of a nation. It aims to create the greatest amount of economic damage possible, thus causing a strong impact on national and [[public opinion]] internationally. Such activity raises the need to create [[Technical standard|industry standards]] to provide some protection against [[terrorist attack]]s.
When more infrastructure and companies are protected by antiterrorism standards, it becomes more expensive, and more time is necessary, to plan an attack on that entity. In this way, [[intelligence agency|intelligence agencies]] and companies can put off an attack and buy time to identify the involved [[terrorist group]]s. Following the [[Madrid terrorist attacks|Madrid]] and [[London terrorist attack 2005|London]] terror attacks, certain companies and service providers in [[Terrorism in Europe|Europe]] are now required by law <ref>[http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri%20=%20CELEX:%2032008L0114:%20EN:%20NOT 2008/114/EC]</ref> to formulate industrial antiterrorism protocols.
==Subjects== The main areas subject to the adoption of anti-terrorism standards are:
* [[Nuclear terrorism|Nuclear]] * Aviation * [[Chemical terrorism|Chemical]] * Petrochemical * Pharmaceutical * Energy * Transport * First Aid * Telecommunications * [[Water terrorism|Water]] * Food
